Now there is a nest box that is already connected to the home wireless network.
Another nest box will need some effort to get online.
Okay, during the day I hung up the new nest box. This is what it looks like in the garden.
But, let's take a quick step back. "What's inside?" Seems like no one has asked.
The top is an ESP32 camera board with a fisheye lens camera, and also an infrared LED that I took off from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box is oddly shaped because the side panel of the nest box can rotate. It was like this when I bought it, and it couldn't be modified, so I had to design according to this situation.
Since there is no power source in the garden, the entire device is powered by a solar panel and a 18650 lithium-ion battery with a capacity of 2600 mAh.
I didn't take photos of the battery or the charger, but this is a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the nest box contains the battery.
After being charged, it can operate for about 4 hours.
I call this a "special feature." This way, the birds also have some private space.
At first, I wasn't sure if the network in the garden was strong enough to support this device. The old access points I replaced last autumn definitely wouldn't work.
However, the coverage of the new access points is completely fine.
Well, I was even planning to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof, pointing it down towards the garden.
If I were to set up more nest boxes with cameras in the future, I might still do it. Especially in places far from the house, I might need it.
Now, the camera has gone offline for some reason I'm not clear about. It stopped working just one hour after sunset.
Perhaps it's because of insufficient light, as it stopped charging three hours before sunset.
Maybe half a day isn't enough time for it to fully charge.
Let's see what happens tomorrow anyway.
I don't have telemetry data for the battery. I might add this feature in a future version.
I think having a few more sensors would be helpful.
Maybe we also need a battery, at least theoretically allowing this thing to last through the whole night.
Oh, and we need to change the lens.
A fisheye lens is really overkill for this.
But I've already browsed components on Digikey, so I might custom design a circuit board specifically for this case.
Or maybe not. We'll see at that time.
And it's still offline.
Awesome.
According to the orientation of the solar panels installed on the house, the actual time that sunlight can reach is only about 90 minutes.
Wait another one or two hours and see if there's any movement (or no movement).
Still offline.
Sigh, truly nothing is easy.
Originally, the 5V and GND lines on the USB-C splitter I used to connect to the battery charger were printed in reverse on the silkscreen.
After swapping the lines, the charging indicator light turned on.
ESP didn't come online immediately, wait a few more minutes.
An hour has passed, and it's still offline.
It seems it's stuck in a reboot loop, triggering the reset function of Tasmota.
This board really sucks. I've ordered a bigger one, hoping it will fix the problem.
Take a look at what I found in the workshop.
This is a 24-volt solar panel. Unfortunately, the sun's angle is too low (and there is also a tree blocking it), so as soon as I connected a load to it, the voltage dropped almost completely.
It looks like I'll have to wait until tomorrow to find out if this solar panel is sufficient, or if I need the ordered higher-performance solar panel.
The information on Amazon shows that this solar panel was bought in 2021, with a maximum output power of 12 volts at 1.2 amps.
So, either there is an issue with this solar panel, or there is an issue with my multimeter, or they changed the product page.
Hello everyone, there is some good news!
They changed the product page, and the one I have is broken.
Both the new and old product pages refer to it as a 12-volt 10-watt solar panel.
This is why I haven't deleted the old email.
Hey, look: this thing reconnected about an hour ago, but only for about half a minute.
Maybe the solar panel charged the battery a little, just enough to run for 38 seconds. That amount of time is only two hours or so.
Guess what: it's cloudy today! So I'm not sure if that (possibly broken) solar panel can generate enough electricity to do the job.
Let's wait and see.
Latest update: the new solar panel is installed and it seems to be working properly now.
It might go offline once the sun sets, but let's wait and see.
Interestingly: I'm using the ping integration feature of Home Assistant to monitor if it's online.
The average round-trip time is 102 milliseconds. It's neither good nor bad.
